HEADWORD: Lytta
<hw>Lyt"ta</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"t⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Lytt⟦ae⟧</plw> <pr>(-t⟦emac⟧)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L., a worm said to grow under the tongue of dogs, and to cause
canine madness, fr. Gr. <grk>ly`tta</grk>, <grk>ly`ssa</grk>, lit.,
madness.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A fibrous and muscular band
lying within the longitudinal axis of the tongue in many mammals, as the
dog.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>


